[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: Conversational Care Coordination Grounded In Episode Plans, Provider-System Integration, and Care-Management Workflows
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why Care Coordination Has Resisted Digital Tools For Two Decades
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Care coordination, as a clinical workflow, has been a phone-and-fax-and-clinic-centric problem for several decades. The reason is structural. Coordination requires a single mind holding the whole picture: the patient's diagnoses, the patient's care plans across all of those diagnoses, the patient's current medications, the patient's allergies, the patient's psychosocial situation, the patient's preferences, the patient's insurance, the patient's open referrals, the patient's open authorizations, the patient's scheduled appointments, the patient's pending test results, the patient's recent care transitions, the patient's care-team roster, the patient's adherence patterns, and the next-best-action across all of those dimensions. Nurse navigators and care managers and care coordinators do this. They do it well when they have time and access. The fundamental constraint, for the past several decades, has been that they do not have time and access for the entire population that would benefit. The patients who get care coordination are typically the highest-risk five to ten percent. The patients in the broad middle (the ones with two or three conditions, the ones in the middle of an episode of moderate complexity, the ones whose Medicaid plan does not include care management, the ones who do not qualify for the cancer center's nurse navigator panel) navigate the system on their own.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing nurse navigators do, when they do it well, is hold a longitudinal model of the patient in their heads, supplemented by chart review, supplemented by phone calls, supplemented by a patchwork of spreadsheets and case-management software. The model includes "what is the current episode (the active care journey)," "what are the open tasks across the episode," "where is the patient relative to plan," "what are the friction points (the appointment that has not been scheduled, the auth that has stalled, the test result that is overdue, the referral that has not closed)," "what is the patient's stated psychosocial context that affects their ability to comply," "what is the relationship status between me and the patient," and "what does the patient need next." Holding this model is most of the cognitive work; the actual phone calls and messages are the easy part once the model is in place.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The first generation of digital coordination tools, roughly the early 2000s through the mid-2010s, tried to systematize the data part of this without the doer part. Care-management software let nurses document cases, tracked open tasks, and produced reports. The clinical evidence for these tools, on their own, was modest; they made the existing nurse-navigator workforce somewhat more productive but did not extend coordination support to the broad middle. The second generation, roughly 2015 to 2022, layered patient-facing portals and apps on top of care-management software. Patients could see their appointments, their test results, their medications, and their open authorizations. Some platforms added care-team messaging. The portals were better than nothing and are now standard across the U.S. healthcare system. The fundamental constraint did not change: the portal is a viewer; coordination is a doer's job; and the portal's existence does not by itself reduce the cognitive load on the patient or close the dropped-ball gaps.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing that changed the workflow shape is, again, large language models that can carry on a coherent, sustained, useful conversation with a patient about their care, with access to the patient's chart, the open tasks, the upcoming appointments, the pending authorizations, the recent care transitions, the care-team roster, and the institutional protocols for episode types. A coordination assistant, deployed with careful institutional governance, can hold the longitudinal model the nurse navigator holds (it has the data, it has the conversation history, it has the task list), can engage in the kinds of focused, timely, helpful conversations the navigator would have, can scale to the broad middle of the population that nurse navigation cannot reach, and can escalate to the human navigator when escalation is warranted. The LLM is not a navigator. The LLM is, in the right product design, a tool that lets the nurse-navigator workflow operate at population scale.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The architectural shift is from "viewer-of-records" to "orchestrator-of-tasks-and-engagement." The assistant's value is concentrated in three places: the coordination-load reduction (catching dropped balls and orchestrating next steps so the patient does not have to), the patient-facing engagement (turning the bewildering information cascade after a complex diagnosis into a sequence of manageable conversations), and the operational reach (extending the care-management workforce's effective coverage from the high-risk minority to the broad middle of the medically complex population).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What a Care Coordination Assistant Actually Does
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A care coordination assistant is a tool-using LLM with a system prompt that tells it which assistant it is, the patient's authenticated context (active episode or episodes, problem list, current medications, allergies, recent encounters, pending orders, open referrals, open authorizations, scheduled appointments, recent test results, recent care transitions, care-team roster, conversation history with the assistant over time, patient-stated preferences and circumstances), access to a structured library of episode-type protocols (what does a new-cancer-diagnosis journey look like, what does a knee-replacement journey look like, what does a maternity journey look like, what does a CHF discharge journey look like, what does a longitudinal multi-condition coordination look like), and a careful set of tools for retrieving and updating coordination state, surfacing open tasks, surfacing friction points, scheduling appointments through the institution's scheduling system, sending follow-up messages, escalating to human care coordinators, and writing back coordination events to the institution's care-management workflow.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The conversation surface is not one conversation. It is a stream of conversational episodes, mostly initiated by the assistant per the episode protocol (the most common pattern in coordination is proactive: the assistant is checking in because something is supposed to happen), sometimes initiated by the patient, sometimes triggered by a system event (an order was placed, an authorization status changed, an appointment was scheduled or cancelled, a test result came back, a discharge happened), sometimes triggered by a care-team event (the navigator added a task, the care-management software flagged a friction point).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The assistant's task surface decomposes roughly as follows.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Episode initiation and care-plan introduction.** The patient is enrolled in coordination by an event in the system: a new diagnosis with a defined episode protocol (a new cancer diagnosis triggers an oncology coordination episode), a planned procedure (a scheduled total knee replacement triggers a perioperative coordination episode), a high-risk discharge (a heart-failure discharge triggers a transitions-of-care episode), or a longitudinal coordination assignment (a high-complexity multi-condition patient is assigned to longitudinal coordination by the care-management team). The first conversation introduces the assistant, sets expectations about what it can and cannot do, gathers any patient-stated preferences (preferred channels, quiet hours, language, who else is allowed to be involved on their behalf, things the patient does not want to discuss), and walks the patient through the high-level shape of the upcoming episode at the level of detail the patient can absorb. The introduction tone is warm but boundaried: the assistant is a coordination tool deployed by the patient's care team, and the patient should know what it is.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Appointment and referral tracking with proactive nudges.** The assistant tracks every appointment and referral in the patient's open coordination state. The assistant nudges when an appointment is upcoming (with appropriate visit-prep content per the institution's intake protocols, often delegating to the pre-visit-intake bot from recipe 11.4), when an appointment was missed and needs to be rescheduled, when a referral was placed but not yet scheduled, when an appointment was scheduled but the patient may need help with logistics (transportation, parking, where to go, what to bring), and when a referral has closed and the patient may want to know what came next. The proactive engagement cadence is set by the episode protocol, not by the LLM.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Prior-authorization status surfacing.** The assistant retrieves prior-authorization status from the institution's authorization workflow tooling, surfaces it conversationally for the patient ("your authorization for the surgical procedure was approved yesterday; the surgical team has been notified and your scheduled date is confirmed"), nudges when an authorization is in a state that needs patient action (a peer-to-peer review request, a request for additional information from the patient or the referring physician, a denial that may need an appeal), and routes the patient to the appropriate human resource when the authorization workflow is stuck. The assistant does not file authorizations; it surfaces and nudges.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Medication-reconciliation support across specialists.** The assistant maintains the patient's current medication list as understood by the institution's record system and as augmented by the patient's reports. The assistant flags discrepancies that are clinically meaningful (a new medication added by one specialist that the other specialists may not be aware of, a medication that the patient reports they have stopped that the chart still says they are on, a medication that has a clinically significant interaction with a treatment being planned). The assistant does not adjust medications; it surfaces discrepancies and routes to the appropriate clinician.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-transition watching.** The assistant pays particular attention to transitions of care: hospital admission, hospital-to-skilled-nursing, hospital-to-home, hospital-to-home-with-home-health, ED-to-PCP, specialist-to-PCP, post-procedure follow-up. Each transition has known failure modes (medication-reconciliation gaps, follow-up-appointment-not-scheduled gaps, durable-medical-equipment delivery gaps, home-health setup gaps, prior-authorization gaps for post-discharge services). The assistant watches for the specific failure modes per the episode protocol, surfaces them when they occur, and engages the patient or escalates to the care-management team as appropriate.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Test-result tracking with appropriate framing.** The assistant tracks pending test results and surfaces them conversationally when they post, with appropriate framing about who will discuss the result and when. The assistant does not interpret clinically meaningful results (a positive biopsy, a markedly abnormal lab); the assistant surfaces that the result is in, says who will be in touch and when, and routes to the care team if the patient has questions the assistant should not answer. The assistant's role is to close the loop on "is the result back," not to deliver clinical interpretations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-specialist plan reconciliation.** Patients with complex episodes have multiple care plans from multiple specialists. The assistant maintains a working view of the integrated plan and surfaces conflicts (the cardiologist wants the patient to walk thirty minutes a day; the orthopedic surgeon has the patient non-weight-bearing for six weeks post-op; this is a conflict the patient cannot resolve and that should be flagged to the care-management team or the appropriate clinician). The assistant does not resolve clinical conflicts; it surfaces them.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Visit preparation orchestration.** Before each scheduled appointment, the assistant orchestrates visit preparation: confirms the patient knows where to go and what to bring, ensures the pre-visit intake bot (recipe 11.4) has captured the relevant intake information, confirms any pre-visit-required testing or imaging is scheduled and completed, surfaces specific questions the patient may want to ask given the episode context, and (where supported) provides the patient with a structured pre-visit summary they can share with the visiting clinician.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Visit follow-up orchestration.** After each scheduled appointment, the assistant follows up: confirms the visit happened, captures any patient-reported takeaways, surfaces any new orders or referrals that resulted, and integrates them into the coordination state. The assistant uses any after-visit-summary content (recipe 2.5) the institution generates to ground its understanding of what happened in the visit.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-episode awareness for multi-episode patients.** Patients with multiple concurrent episodes (a cancer patient who is also pregnant; a transplant patient who is also managing chronic kidney disease; a heart-failure patient who has just had a hip fracture) have coordination across episodes that is more than the sum of the parts. The assistant maintains cross-episode awareness with explicit conflict detection.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient-team communication facilitation.** The assistant facilitates communication between the patient and the care team, both directions. Patient-to-team: the assistant captures the patient's questions or concerns and routes them as structured messages to the appropriate team member. Team-to-patient: the assistant delivers messages from the care team in conversational form, with appropriate framing and the option for follow-up questions. The assistant is not a secure-messaging system; it is a conversational interface that interoperates with the institution's secure-messaging system.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Escalation to human care coordination.** When the situation requires more than the assistant can offer (a clinical question the assistant should not answer, an authorization denial that needs appeal, a coordination problem that requires phone-mediated relationship work, a patient psychosocial concern that requires the social worker or care manager, a patient request for a human, a coordination gap that has crossed the institutional escalation threshold), the assistant routes to the appropriate human resource per the institution's policy, with full conversation context and structured task summary attached.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-team reporting and coordination-event-stream contribution.** The care-management team has visibility into the assistant's interactions with the patient. The assistant generates structured summaries (alerts in real time, weekly digests, episode-completion summaries) that the care-management team reviews. The assistant's role is not to replace the care-management team's judgment; it is to give the care-management team the information they need to deploy their judgment efficiently across a much larger panel.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why a Generic LLM Cannot Run a Care Coordination Assistant
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A naive product approach would be: take a generalist LLM, give it a chat surface, let it answer patient questions about their care. This breaks in several specific ways, each of which has clinical, operational, and compliance consequences.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no view of the institutional coordination state.** Without a structured retrieval surface to the patient's open referrals, scheduled appointments, pending authorizations, recent test results, and care-team roster, the LLM is reduced to whatever the patient happens to mention in conversation. A coordination assistant without coordination-state retrieval is a chatbot that pretends to coordinate without actually coordinating.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no episode-protocol awareness.** Each episode type (new cancer diagnosis, perioperative, post-discharge, maternity, transplant, longitudinal multi-condition, others) has known steps, known checkpoints, known friction points, and known escalation criteria. Without explicit episode protocols, the LLM produces generic "let me know how you're doing" engagement that is not coordination work. Episode protocols are clinical-leadership-owned content, not LLM emergent properties.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model invents coordination steps that do not match institutional reality.** If the LLM is not grounded in the institution's actual referral process, the actual scheduling protocols, the actual authorization workflows, and the actual care-management policies, the LLM produces helpful-sounding suggestions that are wrong for the institution's actual operations. The patient who follows the LLM's freestyled suggestions ends up in a worse position than the patient who follows the actual protocol.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of when to engage proactively versus reactively.** The coordination assistant's value depends substantially on proactive engagement: catching the dropped balls, nudging at the right moments, watching transitions, closing referral loops. A reactive bot that only responds when the patient initiates is useful but is not a coordination assistant. The proactive engagement scheduling is encoded in the episode protocols and triggered by event streams, not by the LLM.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of cross-system task tracking.** Coordination is, structurally, a task-tracking problem. The institutional coordination state lives across multiple back-office systems (the EHR, the referral-management system, the prior-authorization system, the scheduling system, the pharmacy system, the home-health vendor systems, the DME vendor systems, the lab and imaging systems, the care-management workflow tool). The assistant's tool surface includes structured retrieval and (in some cases) structured update across these systems; the LLM does not invent the cross-system integration.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has clinical-decision-rule arithmetic and date-arithmetic problems for coordination.** Coordination is full of date arithmetic: "the surgery is in 11 days; the patient should hold the Eliquis 5 days prior; the cardiology clearance must be on file 7 days prior; the pre-op blood work must be drawn within 30 days of surgery; the home-health intake must happen within 48 hours of discharge." The LLM does this poorly. The deterministic date-and-rule tools encapsulate the computation; the LLM gathers the inputs and presents the result in conversational form.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has scope-discipline failures around clinical questions.** Patients in coordination conversations frequently ask clinical questions: "is this side effect normal," "should I take this medication today," "what does this lab result mean," "is this symptom an emergency." The coordination assistant's scope is administrative and informational, not clinical. The assistant routes clinical questions to the appropriate clinical resource (triage bot, care manager, on-call clinician, after-hours line, 911) per the institution's policy. Without explicit scope discipline, the LLM tries to be helpful and crosses into clinical territory the assistant should not occupy.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has compliance implications for the cross-system access pattern.** The coordination assistant has read access to substantial PHI across multiple back-office systems. The audit, retention, access-control, and data-minimization story has to handle each system's access pattern with state-specific precision. The institutional information-security and compliance teams are part of the architectural design.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of when the patient is in active emergency.** When the patient surfaces a possible emergency (severe pain, severe shortness of breath, suicidal ideation, suspected stroke, severe bleeding) in a coordination conversation, the response is not "let me check your scheduled appointments." The response is to recognize the acuity, route immediately to triage or to direct emergency contacts, and stay present until the routing is complete. The continuous emergency-screening pipeline is non-negotiable.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of mandatory-reporting disclosures.** Coordination conversations sometimes surface disclosures with statutory reporting implications: child abuse, elder abuse, intimate-partner violence. The assistant routes to a licensed clinician (mandatory reporter) with the conversation context attached.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of cross-episode conflict detection.** A patient with multiple concurrent episodes has plans from multiple specialists that may conflict. The cross-episode conflict-detection logic is structured rule-based work over the institutional data; the LLM does not reliably catch the conflicts on its own.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of the boundary between coordination and clinical decision support.** The line between "your appointment with the surgical oncologist is on Tuesday at 10am, here's what to bring" (administrative coordination, in scope) and "based on the imaging results, you should consider asking about whether radiation should come before surgery" (clinical-decision-influencing recommendation, out of scope) matters. The institutional regulatory and clinical-leadership team owns the boundary, and the assistant's prompt and output safety enforce it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What the Coordination Assistant Has To Do That the Previous Bots Did Not
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Recipes 11.1 through 11.8 established the patterns this recipe inherits: input safety screening with continuous emergency screening, identity verification, tool-use orchestration, output safety screening, audit logging, per-cohort monitoring, scope discipline, prompt-injection defense, graceful degradation, longitudinal-context loading, citation grounding, behavior-change-stage tracking (for chronic-disease coaching), and crisis-screening-and-warm-handoff (for mental-health support). The coordination assistant adds eight structural commitments those recipes did not have.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-system coordination state as architectural primitive.** The coordination assistant's longitudinal store is not just conversation history and stated preferences; it is a unified view of the patient's coordination state assembled from multiple back-office systems (EHR, referral-management, prior-authorization, scheduling, pharmacy, home-health vendors, DME vendors, lab, imaging, care-management workflow). The unified-coordination-state architecture is the single largest engineering investment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Episode-protocol-as-code with care-management-leadership ownership.** Each episode type (new cancer diagnosis, perioperative, post-discharge by condition, maternity, transplant, longitudinal multi-condition, and others as the institution defines) has a structured protocol, owned by the appropriate clinical-and-care-management leadership, version-controlled, and reviewed annually. The protocol defines the steps, the cadence, the friction-point watchers, the escalation criteria, the integration points with other workflows, and the operational owners. Skipping the protocol-leadership ownership produces an assistant that is technically functional and operationally untethered.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Proactive-engagement scheduling driven by episode events, not LLM creativity.** The assistant's proactive engagement is driven by the episode protocol and triggered by system events (an order was placed, an authorization status changed, an appointment was scheduled or cancelled, a test result came back, a discharge happened, a transition occurred). The LLM does not decide when to engage; the protocol and the event stream do.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-system action via tool calls, not freestyle.** When the assistant takes an action (schedules an appointment, sends a message to a care-team member, escalates to a human navigator, files a coordination event), the action is taken through a tool call to the institutional system, with full audit trail. The LLM does not invent actions outside the tool surface.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-management workforce integration as primary operational architecture.** The assistant is operationally integrated with the institution's care-management workforce. The care-management team has visibility, has a feedback path, has tooling for handoffs in both directions (assistant escalates to human; human delegates to assistant), and the operational integration is part of production scope.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Scope discipline between administrative coordination and clinical decision support.** The boundary is institutionally specified, reviewed by clinical leadership and regulatory counsel, and enforced through prompt design, output safety, and the conversation review process. The assistant stays administrative; clinical decisions route to humans.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient communication surface as governed channel.** The assistant operates within the institution's patient-communication policy, including TCPA compliance for SMS, BAA scope per channel, encryption posture, retention rules, and (where applicable) state-specific patient-communication regulations. The institution's communications-and-marketing leadership is part of the policy review where the assistant's outreach overlaps with non-coordination outreach.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome measurement against episode-level metrics.** The assistant's clinical-and-operational performance is measured against episode-level outcomes (treatment-plan-completion rate, time-to-treatment-start, readmission rate, prior-authorization turnaround time, referral-closure rate, medication-reconciliation rate, patient-reported coordination quality). The outcome-correlation pipeline is multi-quarter post-launch work.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The rest is largely the same as the previous chapter 11 recipes: tool-surface contract management, identity-assurance lifecycle, conversation logging, scope filtering, per-cohort monitoring, graceful degradation when upstream systems fail.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Coordination Reality
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few notes on what makes care coordination specifically harder than the other patient-facing bot use cases.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The integration surface is the project.** Most of the engineering work in a care coordination assistant is integration with the institutional back-office systems. The EHR integration, the referral-management integration, the prior-authorization integration, the scheduling integration, the pharmacy integration, the home-health-vendor integration, the DME-vendor integration, the lab and imaging integration, the care-management-workflow-tool integration. Each integration is a project. Each integration has its own access pattern, its own data model, its own update cadence, its own reliability profile, and its own contractual posture. Most institutions discover, six months in, that the integration work is the project, and that the LLM is a comparatively small part of the total engineering effort.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Source-of-truth variability is the second engineering problem.** The patient's "current medication list" is different in the EHR's medication module, in the patient's portal-displayed medication list, in the pharmacy's fill history, in the patient's recollection, and in the most recent specialist's note. Each source has a use case where it is the right answer and a use case where it is the wrong answer. The coordination assistant makes structured decisions about which source-of-truth to use for which question; the institutional clinical informatics leadership owns these decisions; the assistant's tool surface implements them.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-management workforce coordination is the operational problem.** The assistant operates alongside human care managers, nurse navigators, and care coordinators. The assistant's escalation pathway, the human-to-assistant delegation pathway, the alert design, the digest cadence, and the tooling are negotiated with the workforce in production, not designed in a vacuum and shipped at them. Building this without active care-management-team involvement produces an assistant the workforce does not use, which is an expensive failure mode.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Episode protocol completeness is multi-quarter clinical work.** Each episode protocol is a specification of what is supposed to happen, when, by whom, with what dependencies, with what escalation criteria. Most institutions discover, partway through development, that the institution's actual practice for these episode types is partially documented, varies across clinicians, and has gaps the formalization process surfaces. Closing the gaps is multi-quarter clinical-and-operations work.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Authorization-system reality is harder than authorization theory.** Prior authorization is governed by payer-specific rules, payer-specific timelines, payer-specific submission channels, payer-specific information requirements, and payer-specific appeal processes. Where the institution operates as a multi-payer environment (most do), the authorization assistant's scope spans every payer the institution contracts with. Each payer's authorization rules can change. Each payer's submission system can change. The assistant's authorization-status surfacing is bounded by the integration the institution has built; full automation of authorization filing is out of scope for most coordination assistants.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient psychosocial context is part of the coordination work.** Patients in complex episodes have psychosocial context that affects coordination: caregiver availability, transportation, language, financial pressure, work-schedule constraints, housing stability, food security, child-care responsibilities, cultural and religious considerations. The assistant captures this context where the patient discloses it, surfaces it to the care-management team where appropriate, and adjusts its engagement accordingly. Coordination that ignores psychosocial context is coordination that produces plans the patient cannot follow.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Caregiver and family-member involvement is structurally common.** Coordination patients often have family members or caregivers who are part of the navigation: the adult child of an elderly patient, the spouse of a cancer patient, the parent of a pediatric patient. The institutional consent posture for caregiver involvement is reviewed by legal and clinical leadership, the assistant's interaction model accommodates authorized caregivers (with appropriate consent capture), and the audit posture preserves who-said-what across patient and caregiver.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Episode duration and intensity vary widely.** A perioperative knee-replacement episode may be 90 days from pre-op to post-op recovery completion. A new cancer diagnosis may be a 12-to-24-month treatment journey followed by years of survivorship. A maternity episode is roughly 9 months prenatal plus 6 weeks postpartum. A longitudinal multi-condition coordination is open-ended. The assistant's engagement intensity, content focus, and escalation thresholds all vary with episode type.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cultural and linguistic considerations are not optional.** Coordination patients are a representative cross-section of the institution's population, with the disparities in coordination access and outcome that the population has historically experienced. Per-cohort monitoring is essential, and per-language deployment is part of production scope.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-episode-conflict detection is a specific architectural concern.** Multi-episode patients (a cancer patient who is also pregnant; a transplant patient with chronic kidney disease; a heart-failure patient who has just had a hip fracture) have plans that may conflict. Detecting conflicts requires cross-episode awareness and structured rule-based logic.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The patient's relationship to the coordination assistant is meaningfully different in different episode types.** A new-cancer-diagnosis patient experiencing the assistant for the first time is at a moment of high distress and information overload; a longitudinal multi-condition patient has been working with the assistant for two years; a maternity patient is generally healthy but is navigating a high-stakes life event. The assistant's tone, cadence, and content adapt; the per-episode-type calibration is reviewed by clinical leadership and patient-experience leadership.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Liability exposure is meaningfully different from the previous chapter 11 recipes.** A coordination assistant is interacting with patients in serious episodes where dropped balls have serious consequences. The institutional malpractice carrier and behavioral-health-and-medical liability counsel review the assistant's design, scope, escalation pathway, and audit posture.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Where the Field Has Moved
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few practical updates worth knowing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-management software has matured into a stable category.** Several mature commercial vendors operate care-management workflow tooling at major-payer and major-health-system scale, with case-management functionality, task tracking, alert routing, population-level reporting, and (increasingly) patient-facing surfaces. <!-- TODO: verify; the care-management software category includes vendors like Epic Healthy Planet, Salesforce Health Cloud, Innovaccer, Lightbeam, and others; specific feature parity and market share varies --> Most major institutions deploying a coordination assistant integrate with their existing care-management workflow rather than replacing it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **FHIR-based interoperability has improved across institutional integrations.** FHIR resources for CarePlan, CareTeam, ServiceRequest (referrals), Task, Appointment, MedicationRequest, MedicationStatement, Observation, DiagnosticReport, Encounter, AllergyIntolerance, Communication, and others provide structured retrieval surfaces that map well to coordination work. <!-- TODO: verify; FHIR R4 and later resources for care coordination are well-specified; institutional FHIR API maturity varies --> The TEFCA framework is contributing to cross-institutional data exchange, which is increasingly relevant for coordination across health systems.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Tool-using LLMs handle coordination orchestration well when grounded carefully.** The function-calling pattern from previous chapter 11 recipes maps to coordination. The LLM produces tool calls that retrieve coordination state, surface friction points, schedule appointments through institutional scheduling systems, send messages through institutional secure-messaging systems, escalate to human care coordinators, and post events for downstream operations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Hybrid AI-plus-human coordination is the dominant production pattern.** Most major deployments run a hybrid model: AI assistant for routine coordination across the broad medically-complex population, with human navigator availability for high-complexity episodes, escalation cases, and patient-requested human contact. The economics work because the AI assistant handles the tracking-and-nudging volume while the human navigator focuses on the cases requiring judgment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome measurement frameworks for coordination are improving.** Per-episode coordination-quality metrics (treatment-plan-completion rate, time-to-treatment-start, readmission rate, prior-authorization turnaround time, referral-closure rate, medication-reconciliation rate, patient-reported coordination quality) are increasingly standard. <!-- TODO: verify; care-coordination quality metrics including the AHRQ Care Coordination Quality Measures and the NCQA care-management program accreditation criteria provide established measurement frameworks; specific metric definitions vary --> Institutional dashboards measure these metrics over time and per-cohort.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Equity and access disparities in coordination are an active concern.** The patients with the highest coordination need are often the patients with the most limited access to and comfort with digital tools. <!-- TODO: verify; disparities in care-coordination access and outcomes have been documented in multiple studies of healthcare-system populations --> Per-cohort monitoring is essential, and multi-channel deployment (SMS-first, voice-channel option, language access from day one) is part of equity-oriented production scope.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Build-vs-buy is mature for some segments.** Several mature commercial vendors offer care-coordination products at major-payer and major-health-system scale. Most major institutions run a hybrid: build a thin orchestration layer in-house on the institution's preferred infrastructure, partner with vendors for specific episode-content libraries (oncology navigation, transplant navigation, complex-care management), and integrate with the institution's care-management workflow tooling.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
